ith a screechy voice, derived from <i>krek</i> ‘screechy voice of a tern and some other birds’ (compare with the Czech name below).","Czech (<b>Křek</b>): nickname for someone with a characteristic voice, from <i>(s)křek</i> ‘screech’."],"variants":[{"name":"Kraker","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Hans, Erwin, Fritz, Otto.","Slovenian: variant of <b>Krakar</b>, a nickname derived from <i>krakati</i> ‘to croak’ (see 2 below) or, perhaps, from <i>krak</i> ‘hindleg of a frog’, figuratively ‘long leg’ (see   Krek   1). Compare   Kracker  .","German: nickname for someone with a croaky voice, derived from (or under the influence of) Slovenian <i>krakati</i> ‘to croak’, or a Germanized form of Slovenian <b>Krakar</b> (see 1 above). It is an Austrian surname, originating from the (bilingual) Austrian parts of Carinthia and Styria, and a Gottscheerish (i.e. Gottschee German) surname, originating from the Kočevsko region in Lower Carniola, Slovenia (see   Kocevar  )."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Geoffrey Crek was born about 1185, in Europe. He married Miss de la Haye of Essex before 1214, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"ABT 1185–":"umbes 1185–Surnud","1190–Female":"1190–Surnud","1214–Female":"1214–Surnud","1185–Male":"1185–Surnud","1190":"1190","ABT 1185":"umbes 1185","before 1214":"enne 1214","1214":"1214","1185":"1185","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, England"},"fi":{"ABT 1185–":"noin 1185–Kuollut","1190–Female":"1190–Kuollut","1214–Female":"1214–Kuollut","1185–Male":"1185–Kuollut","1190":"1190","ABT 1185":"noin 1185","before 1214":"ennen vuotta 1214","1214":"1214","1185":"1185","Europe":"Europe","England":"England","Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, England"},"fr":{"ABT 1185–":"environ 1185–Décédé","1190–Female":"1190–Décédée","1214–Female":"1214–Décédée","1185–Male":"1185–Décédé","1190":"1190","ABT 1185":"environ 1185","before 1214":"avant 1214","1214":"1214","1185":"1185","Europe":"Europe","England":"Angleterre","Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Geoffrey Crek est né environ 1185, à Europe. Il a épousé Miss de la Haye of Essex avant 1214, à Angleterre. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"ABT 1185–":"um 1185–Verstorben","1190–Female":"1190–Verstorben","1214–Female":"1214–Verstorben","1185–Male":"1185–Verstorben","1190":"1190","ABT 1185":"um 1185","before 1214":"vor 1214","1214":"1214","1185":"1185","Europe":"Europa","England":"England","Halstead, Essex, England":"Halstead, Essex, England","lifeSummary":"Geoffrey Crek wurde um 1185 in Europa geboren. Er hat vor 1214 in England Miss de la Haye of Essex geheiratet. Sie hatten mindestens 1 Tochter."},"ht":{"ABT 1185–":"about 1185–Desede","1190–Female":"1190–Desede","1214–Female":"1214–Desede","1185–Male":"1185–Desede","1190":"1190","ABT 1185":"about 1185","be